  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Hungary's healthcare is adequate for most needs, with private facilities in Budapest providing good care. Complex conditions may warrant travel to Vienna or other major European centers—easily accessible given Hungary's location.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Budapest private hospitals</strong> include facilities like Medicover Hospital, Duna Medical Center, and various private clinics offering good care for routine and moderate-complexity conditions. These facilities have modern equipment and often English-speaking staff. Direct billing with international insurers is common.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Public hospitals</strong> (állami kórház) provide comprehensive care but can involve waiting times, crowded conditions, and variable quality depending on facility. Major teaching hospitals like Semmelweis University clinics provide good care. Public healthcare is improving but still catching up to Western European standards.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Vienna connection:</strong> Austria's capital—with world-class hospitals like AKH Vienna—is 2.5 hours by train. Many Hungary-based retirees use Vienna for complex procedures, second opinions, or specialized care. International insurance facilitates this cross-border care seamlessly.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Thermal medicine:</strong> Hungary's thermal baths are genuinely therapeutic, not just recreational. Medical spa treatments (using thermal waters for rehabilitation, arthritis, and musculoskeletal conditions) are covered by some insurance plans. This unique resource benefits retirees with joint pain, mobility issues, or chronic conditions responsive to balneotherapy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Pharmacies (gyógyszertár) are well-stocked with European medications. Prices are lower than Western Europe. Some medications require Hungarian prescriptions—bring documentation from home. English is increasingly common in Budapest pharmacies but not guaranteed.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Hungary offers excellent value for Central Europe—significantly cheaper than Austria, Germany, or Western Europe while providing European standards and EU membership benefits. Currency is the forint (HUF), though Euro is sometimes accepted.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement with comprehensive health coverage typically ranges from €1,800-2,800 depending on location and lifestyle. Central Budapest comfortable retirement runs €2,000-2,800; Buda hills €2,200-3,000; Lake Balaton area €1,600-2,400.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare cost strategy:</strong> International insurance costs €350-700/month for seniors. Hungarian private insurance (€100-300/month) provides local coverage at lower cost. Using Hungarian coverage for routine care plus international insurance for complex care and travel provides good value.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Currency considerations:</strong> Hungary uses the forint, not the Euro. Exchange rates fluctuate—when the forint weakens, your Euro/dollar income buys more. Most retirees maintain accounts in both currencies for flexibility.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Thermal spa value:</strong> Daily thermal bath access costs just €10-20 at major facilities. Annual passes are even cheaper. This affordable wellness amenity significantly enhances quality of life, particularly for retirees with joint or mobility issues.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Hungarian a difficult language?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes—Hungarian is unrelated to neighboring languages and genuinely challenging. However, English is increasingly common in Budapest, especially among younger people and in tourist/expat areas. Many retirees manage with English plus basic Hungarian phrases.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How cold are Budapest winters?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Cold—December through February averages around freezing with some days well below. Snow is common. Central heating in apartments is standard and effective. The cold is continental European—comparable to Chicago or Vienna. Not extreme but definitely winter.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Should I go to Vienna for serious medical care?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">For complex conditions, yes—Vienna has world-class facilities. For routine care and most conditions, Budapest's private facilities are adequate. Your insurance's advice line can help determine when Vienna's superior resources justify the trip.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What about Hungary's political situation?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Hungary's government has been controversial internationally. This affects some expats' comfort levels. Day-to-day life for foreign retirees is largely unaffected. EU membership provides stability guardrails. Personal political comfort varies—research current conditions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Are thermal baths really beneficial for health?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Evidence supports benefits for arthritis, joint pain, and musculoskeletal conditions. Hungarian medical tradition includes balneotherapy (therapeutic bathing) as legitimate treatment. Many retirees report significant quality of life improvements from regular thermal bathing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Budapest safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes—one of Europe's safer major cities. Violent crime is rare; petty theft exists in tourist areas. Standard urban precautions suffice. The city is generally walkable and safe at night in most neighborhoods. Crime rates are lower than most Western European capitals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Hungary Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers experienced with Hungary retirement. Coverage that works locally and provides access to European specialists."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
